  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Envelop 1: Provision of Innovative and Dignified Integrated Shelter Units to the most vulnerable IDPs in NW Syria</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to provide an innovative shelter solution to 386 HH (1961 individuals) (Breakdown: 263Men, 386 Women, 540 Boys, and 772 Girls) the most vulnerable IDPs in Idleb sub-district in the following camps:
1- Althawra camp (Pcode: CP001982) 125 HH
2- Ritco Camp (Pcode: CP000709) 126 HH
3- Al Shuhadaa(Idleb) (Pcode: CP001981) 135 HH


The proposed shelter solution is manufactured by sandwich panels and steel metal frame in TRC factory in Malatya.

The shelter unit consists of one room 18 sq. meters (6*3) in addition to the kitchen, toilet, and bathroom with a total size of 25.5 sq. meters.

This project will be implemented in a partnership between TRC and Mercy-USA (as sub-IP).

To have clear roles responsibilities for each partner we can explain as follows:

TRC Role:
1-TRC will purchase and deliver the shelter units from Turkey to Zero points in Cilvegozu-Bab Alhawa borders
2- Periodic Monitoring for all activities
3-Compile narrative and financial reports

Mercy-USA Role:
During the project design, Mercy-USA conducted a Need assessment to identify the exact needs and site management and topographic studies to calculate the BOQ needed
1-Mercy-USA will deliver shelter units from the zero points to the final destination, and install them through daily workers in the predetermined camps.
2-Mercy-USA will do all infrastructure preparations including Digging and backfilling soil, Extending the pipes: 4 inches from the toilet in each shelter to the septic tank and 6 inches from septic tanks to the main sewage network, Building investigation chamber, Graveling and Levelling: coarse gravel to diameter (1.6-3.2) cm and thickness 15 cm with compaction and humidification under the shelter units to elevate it above the ground with about 15 cm, and Rainwater collection: by using special pipes in the ceiling to harvest the rain to be collected in one tank between each two shelters
3- Day to day monitoring to ensure quality work is being implemented
4-Community outreach and sensitization
5-HLP due diligence
6-Regular narrative and financial reporting to be shared with TRC


Accountability to the affected population is a key component in this project, so PWD will be identified from the beginning to provide them with special toilets, handrails, as well as ramps to access the shelter.</narrative>
  </description>
